        "title": "Java: best way to declare a stack of cards",
        "body": "<p>I'm trying to make a simple Blackjack application so that I can practice what I have learned from my Java book.  <\/p>\n\n<p>The \"project\" will never be deployed nor is it \"important\" as such, just for me to learn, keeping that in mind what do you think is the best way for me to store the pack of cards?  <\/p>\n\n<p>My choices seem to be simple array, double dimension array, hashmap and arraylist.  <\/p>\n\n<p>Once I get my cards in my collection I think the methods I will build will be:  <\/p>\n\n<p>shuffleDeck() - self explanatory<br>\nremoveCardsFromDeck() - So these cards are \"used\" for the game<br>\nmergeNumberOfDecks(int howMany) - How many decks of cards to merge (eg: 0 or 2 or 4 or 8)<\/p>\n\n<p>Keeping that in mind which do you think would be the easiest to handle:\nsimple array, double dimension array, hashmap or arraylist?<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 19233194,
