    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/rUCgi.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 2888638,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2477916,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2477916/java-devil",
                "reputation": 11079,
                "display_name": "Java Devil",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1381175742,
            "creation_date": 1381175103,
            "body": "<p>Most stack/deck of cards situations are best solved by the use of a <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Deque.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>Deque<\/code><\/a>. Has both List and queue methods and also is a collection so you can do the following.<\/p>\n\n<p>Shuffle: Done by <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/Collections.html#shuffle%28java.util.List%29\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>Collections.shuffle(List)<\/code><\/a> (If your chosen deque also implements List) See <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/LinkedList.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>LinkedList<\/code><\/a> as an example<\/p>\n\n<p>Remove cards: - Ideally top cards, Deque has <code>removeFirst()<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p>Merge: <code>java.util.collection<\/code> has <code>addAll(Collection)<\/code> (so any class that implements collection has this method)  <\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 19233279,
            "question_id": 19233194,
            "last_edit_date": 1381175742
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d376b06cea049485645a4b6a4ec10f92?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 19190,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 44737,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/44737/rob",
                "reputation": 6287,
                "display_name": "rob",
                "accept_rate": 78
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1381175869,
            "creation_date": 1381174975,
            "body": "<p>Of the options you've listed, a <code>List<\/code> probably makes the most sense because it's easy to work with and will preserve the order of your deck after shuffling it.<\/p>\n\n<p>Unless you really want to implement them all yourself, the three methods you mentioned are already implemented.<\/p>\n\n<p>shuffleDeck(): <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Collections.html#shuffle%28java.util.List%29\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>Collections.shuffle(List)<\/code><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>removeCardsFromDeck():<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>For single cards, you can use Collection.remove(Object) and related methods (e.g., List.remove(int index) or <code>LinkedList.removeFirst()<\/code>/<code>LinkedList.removeLast()<\/code> or <code>Stack.pop()<\/code>)  Note that although I'm including Stack as an example, you probably don't want to use it unless you require synchronization.<\/li>\n<li>For multiple cards, you can use <code>Collection.removeAll(Collection)<\/code><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>mergeNumberOfDecks(): there isn't an <code>exact<\/code> analog, but <code>Collection.addAll(Collection)<\/code> will make your job very easy<\/p>\n\n<p>Keep in mind that List inherits all of Collection's methods, and any class that implements List must define implementations for all of List's methods (including those which are inherited from Collection.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 19233244,
            "question_id": 19233194,
            "last_edit_date": 1381175869
        }
    ],
